an money launderers]]\n[[Category:American prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Pennsylvania House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania state senators]]\n[[Category:People convicted of making false statements]]\n[[Category:Community College of Philadelphia alumni]]\n[[Category:Fels Institute of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania Democrats]]\n[[Category:Baptists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:African-American state legislators in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania politicians convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:Politicians convicted of bribery under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 201]]\n[[Category:Politicians convicted of illegal gratuities under 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 201]]\n[[Category:Politicians convicted of mail and wire fraud]]\n[[Category:Politicians convicted of racketeering]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of the United States federal government]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Chaka Fattah\n| image = Chaka Fattah official headshot.jpg\n| state = [[Pennsylvania]]\n| district = [[Pennsylvania's 2nd congressional district|2nd]]\n| term_start = January 3, 1995\n| term_end = June 23, 2016\n| preceded = [[Lucien E. Blackwell|Lucien Blackwell]]\n| succeeded = [[Dwight E. Evans]]\n| state_senate2 =Pennsylvania\n| district2 =[[Pennsylvania Senate, District 7|7th]]\n| term_start2 = January 3, 1989\n| term_end2 = August 31, 1994<ref>{{cite web | last = Cox | first = Harold | title = Pennsylvania Senate \u2013 1993\u20131994| work = [[Wilkes University Election Statistics Project]]| publisher = Wilkes University | year =2004 | url =http://staffweb.wilkes.edu/harold.cox/legis/177S.pdf}}</ref>\n| predecessor2 = [[Freeman Hankins]]\n| successor2 = [[Vincent Hughes]]\n| state_house3 =Pennsylvania\n| district3 =[[Pennsylvania House of Representatives, District 192|192nd]]\n| term_start3 = January 4, 1983\n| term_end3 = November 30, 1988\n| predecessor3 = [[Nicholas A. Pucciarelli|Nick Pucciarelli]]\n| successor3 = [[Louise Bishop]]\n| party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| birth_date= {{birth date and age|1956|11|21}}\n| birth_place= [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| birthname = Arthur Davenport\n| residence= Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, U.S.\n| alma_mater= [[Community College of Philadelphia]]<br>[[University of Pennsylvania]]\n| spouse = [[Renee Chenault-Fattah]]\n| children = Frances Fattah<br>Cameron Chenault<br>Chandler Fattah<br>Chaka Fattah Jr.\n| religion = [[Baptist]]\n}}\n \n'''Chaka Fattah''' (born '''Arthur Davenport''';<ref>[https://history.house.gov/People/Detail/13018]</ref> November 21, 1956) is an American politician from the [[Commonwealth (United States)|Commonwealth]] of [[Pennsylvania]] who served as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] member of the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House]] for {{ushr|PA|2}} from 1995 to 2016.  He previously served in the [[Pennsylvania Senate]] and the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives]].\n\nThe district included portions of [[North Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|North Philadelphia]], [[South Philadelphia]], and [[West Philadelphia]] along with [[Lower Merion Township, Pennsylvania|Lower Merion Township]] in [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Montgomery County]].\n\nOn July 29, 2015, Fattah and a group of associates were indicted on federal charges related to their alleged roles in a [[racketeering]] and [[influence peddling]] [[Conspiracy (criminal)|conspiracy]].<ref name=\"fbi2015\"/><ref>{{cite news|title = Chaka Fattah indictment, full text - CNNPolitics.com|url = http://www.cnn.com/2015/07/29/politics/chaka-fattah-indictment/index.html|website = CNN|accessdate = 2015-07-29}}</ref>  He was convicted on 23 counts of racketeering, fraud, and other corruption charges on June 21, 2016, and resigned two days later.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/rep-chaka-fattah-resigns-after-conviction-effective-immediately/|title=Rep. Chaka Fattah resigns after conviction, effective immediately |publisher=CBS |date=June 23, 2016 |accessdate=2016-06-23}}</ref> On December 12, 2016, Fattah was sentenced to 10 years in prison.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/the-latest-ex-rep-chaka-fattah-sentenced-to-10-years/2016/12/12/83bb1d54-c088-11e6-a52b-a0a126eaf9f7_story.html|title=The Latest: Ex-Rep. Chaka Fattah sentenced to 10 years|website=Washington Post|access-date=2016-12-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/former-congressman-chaka-fattah-sentenced-10-years-prison-participating-racketeering|title=Former Congressman Chaka Fattah Sentenced to 10 Years in Prison for Participating in Racketeering Conspiracy|website=US Department of Justice|date=12 December 2016|access-date=2016-12-14}}</ref>\n\nOn August 9, 2018, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]] in Philadelphia overturned Fattah's bribery convictions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www2.ca3.uscourts.gov/opinarch/164397p.pdf|title=PRECEDENTIAL UNITED STATES COURT OF APPEALS FOR THE THIRD CIRCUIT |last=|first=|date=August 9, 2018|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> On July 12, 2019, a Philadelphia judge sentenced Fattah to 10 years in federal prison for public corruption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://whyy.org/articles/at-resentencing-chaka-fattah-still-gets-10-years/|title=Former Philly lawmaker Chaka Fattah gets same punishments at resentencing hearing|website=WHYY|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inquirer.com/news/chaka-fattah-sentencing-appeal-mcdonnell-third-circuit-harvey-bartle-20190712.html|title=Ex-U.S. Rep. Chaka Fattah sentenced again to 10 years in prison|last=Roebuck|first=Jeremy|website=https://www.inquirer.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nFattah grew up in [[Philadelphia]], attending [[Overbrook High School (Philadelphia)|Overbrook High School]] and the [[Community College of Philadelphia]].<ref name=EDUCATION>[http://www.thenextmayor.com/vault/20061120fattah_school_record.html Chaka Fattah educational background] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927215517/http://www.thenextmayor.com/vault/20061120fattah_school_record.html |date=2007-09-27 }} Philadelphia Daily News</ref> He is a member of [[Alpha Phi Alpha]] fraternity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fattah.house.gov/press/congressman-fattah-receives-honors-from-alpha-phi-alpha-fraternity-at-its-centennial/|title=Congressman Fattah Receives Honors from Alpha Phi Alpha Fraternity at Its Centennial|publisher=Chaka Fattah|date=July 26, 2006|accessdate=July 29, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304204620/http://fattah.house.gov/press/congressman-fattah-receives-honors-from-alpha-phi-alpha-fraternity-at-its-centennial/|archivedate=March 4, 2016}}</ref>  In 1984, Fattah completed the Program for Senior Executives in State and Local Government at [[Harvard University]]'s [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]].  In May 1986, he received his master's degree in Governmental Administration from the [[University of Pennsylvania]]'s [[Fels Institute of Government]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Pennsylvania House of Representatives - Chaka Fattah Biography |url=https://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/BiosHistory/MemBio.cfm?ID=395&body=H |website=legis.state.pa.us |accessdate=1 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nFattah was the recipient of numerous honors and awards including 10 honorary doctorates and the University of Pennsylvania\u2019s Fels Institute of Government Distinguished Alumni Achievement Award.  Time Magazine named Fattah one of the 50 most promising leaders in the country.\n\nHis parents divorced when he was young, and his mother soon remarried to a man she met at a national conference on black power in 1968. Following this conference, his mother decided to change his name to Chaka Fattah, to acknowledge their African ethnicity.<ref>http://pabook2.libraries.psu.edu/palitmap/bios/Fattah__Chaka.html{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nHis adoptive father, David Fattah, and mother, Falaka Fattah (born Frances Brown, also known as \"Queen Mother\" Falaka Fattah), are community activists in West Philadelphia, where they are building an \"urban Boys' Town\" through their organization, the House of Umoja.<ref>{{cite news|title=West Philly House of Umoja Still Inspires Community to End Gang Violence|newspaper=Philadelphia Neighborhoods|date=May 26, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://philadelphianeighborhoods.com/2015/05/26/west-philly-the-house-of-umoja-still-inspires-the-community-to-end-gang-violence |title=West Philly: The House of Umoja Still Inspires the Community to End Gang Violence |publisher=Philadelphia Neighborhoods |date= 26 May 2015|accessdate=2016-04-26}}</ref> He has five brothers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rep. Fattah's path from one House to another|newspaper=Philadelphia Daily News|date=July 25, 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Pennsylvania Legislature==\nFattah served as a member of the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives]] for the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives, District 192|192nd district]] from 1983 to 1988, and as a [[Pennsylvania State Senate|State Senator]] for the [[Pennsylvania Senate, District 7|7th district]] from 1988 to 1994.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pennsylvania State Senate - Chaka Fattah Biography |url=https://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/BiosHistory/MemBio.cfm?ID=4617&body=S |website=legis.state.pa.us |accessdate=1 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, Fattah founded the Graduate Opportunity Initiative Conference, an annual three-day informational and scholarship conference which aims to significantly increase the enrollment of under-represented graduate students studying Science, Technology, Engineering and Math ([[STEM fields]]). The conference was designed to encourage minority students\u2019 interest in STEM graduate and professional schools.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\nIn 1991, State Senator Fattah decided to run for [[Pennsylvania's 2nd congressional district]] in the special election that was held after Democratic U.S. Congressman [[William H. Gray (Pennsylvania politician)|William Gray]] decided to resign. On November 5, 1991, City Councilman [[Lucien Edward Blackwell]] won the election with a plurality of 39% of the vote defeating Fattah (28%), [[John F. White, Jr.|John F. White]] (28%), and Nadine Smith-Bulford (5%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=126365 |title=PA District 2 - Special Election Race - Nov 05, 1991 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-04-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Fattah decided to challenge Blackwell in the Democratic primary. He defeated the incumbent 58%-42%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=375809 |title=PA District 2 - D Primary Race - May 10, 1994 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-04-26}}</ref> He won the general election with 86% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=29311 |title=PA District 2 Race - Nov 08, 1994 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-04-26}}</ref> After that, he was re-elected every two years with at least 86% of the vote. He was never challenged in the Democratic primary until 2016, when he lost to [[Dwight E. Evans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=1623 |title=Candidate - Chaka Fattah |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |accessdate=2016-04-26}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nFattah represented the 2nd district in Pennsylvania, an overwhelmingly Democratic district, in the [[United States House of Representatives]] from 1995 to 2016. Fattah endorsed [[Barack Obama]] for President in 2008.<ref>[http://thehill.com/endorsements-2008.html Endorsements 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080718101229/http://thehill.com/endorsements-2008.html |date=2008-07-18 }}, ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]''</ref>\n\n====GEAR Up and education====\nHe is the architect of the [[Gaining Early Awareness and Readiness for Undergraduate Programs]].\n\nIn his first years in the U.S.  House of Representatives, Fattah introduced and passed into law [[Gaining Early Awareness and Readiness for Undergraduate Programs]] (GEAR UP), a college awareness and preparedness program. Since its inception, more than $4 billion in federal funds have been distributed to assist 12 million students in 50 states, Puerto Rico, the District of Columbia, and U.S. territories.  Fattah sponsored H.R. 4207, American Dream Accounts Act which  would authorize the Department of Education to award three-year competitive grants to support partnerships that provide financial support and preparation for low-income students as they plan for their college education.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fattah Adds Financial Piece to GEAR UP|date=June 2012|url=http://www.crewof42.com/featured/fattah-adds-financial-piece-to-gear-up/|publisher=Crew of 42}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=The \"Assets Effect\"|url=http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/magazine/julyaugust_2012/features/the_assets_effect038418.php|magazine=The Washington Monthly}}</ref>  The bill is co-sponsored in the U. S. Senate by Senator Chris Coons of Delaware, Senator Marco Rubio of Florida and Senator Jeff Bingaman of New Mexico. Specifically the legislation creates personal online accounts for students that monitor higher education readiness and includes a college savings account. The accounts follow students from school to school and through college. Parents can grant vested stakeholders (including counselors, teachers, coaches, mentors, and others) access to the account to update student information, monitor progress, and provide college preparatory support.\n\nFattah has introduced a few bills targeting the equity of resource allocation within and between school districts. In 2002, he introduced the \"Student Bill of Rights\", H.R. 2451.<ref>{{cite web|title=SENATOR DODD AND REPRESENTATIVE FATTAH INTRODUCE THE STUDENT BILL OF RIGHTS ACT OF 2002|url=http://www.all4ed.org/publication_material/straight_as/09092002#Rights|publisher=Alliance for Excellent Education|access-date=2012-08-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101116005625/http://all4ed.org/publication_material/straight_as/09092002#Rights|archive-date=2010-11-16|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The measure calls for States to provide highly effective teachers, early childhood education, college prep curricula and equitable instructional resources to all students who attend public schools. Current law requires that schools within the same district provide comparable educational services; this bill would extend that basic protection to the State level by requiring comparability across school districts.\n \nThe ESEA Fiscal Fairness Act, H.R. 5071 \u2013 amends the Elementary and Secondary Education Act to requires school districts to equalize the real dollars spent among all schools within its jurisdiction \u2013 with the imperative to raise the resources allotted to schools in the poorest neighborhoods to meet those in well-off schools \u2013 before receiving federal aid.<ref>{{cite web|title=Confirming What We Knew: Poor Students Really Do Get a Raw Deal on School Funding|url=http://www.firstfocus.net/news/reading-list/confirming-what-we-knew-poor-students-really-do-get-a-raw-deal-on-school-funding|publisher=First Focus}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Diverse Groups Join Alliance to Close Loophole in Title I Comparability Provision|url=http://www.edtrust.org/dc/press-room/news/diverse-groups-join-alliance-to-close-loophole-in-title-i-comparability-provision|publisher=The Education Trust|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121209230351/http://www.edtrust.org/dc/press-room/news/diverse-groups-join-alliance-to-close-loophole-in-title-i-comparability-provision|archivedate=2012-12-09}}</ref>\n\nFattah introduced \"Communities Committed to College\", H.R. 1579.<ref>{{cite web|title=Summit on Access to Higher Education Held at PhilaU|url=http://wordpress.philau.edu/today/2011/07/25/philau-hosts-summit-on-access-to-higher-education/|publisher=Philadelphia University}}</ref>  The legislation provides a 50% tax credit to donors who contribute to qualifying scholarship trusts that are recognized and registered with the [[Secretary of the Treasury]]. \n \nHe also wrote the legislation for the [[American Opportunity Tax Credit]] (AOTC).  The [[tax credit]] assists any full-time college or university student or their families that claim the credit. Since 2011, it has assisted 4.5million students and their families.{{citation needed|date=September 2012}} AOTC provides up to $2500 tax credit for families to assist them with the cost of college. The credit is unique in that families under a set income without a tax liability are eligible for a tax rebate. President Obama has called for making the tax credit permanent.{{citation needed|date=September 2012}}\nOutside of legislative work Fattah has created a few local education initiatives for Philadelphia and Pennsylvania families as a state legislator and in cooperation with state and municipal governments, including the CORE scholars program and the annual Grad Conference.{{citation needed|date=September 2012}}\n\nCollege Opportunity Resources for Education (CORE) is an initiative providing almost $27 million in last-dollar scholarships to over 18,000 students.<ref>{{cite web|title=CORE Scholarships|date=8 November 2016|url=http://www.corescholars.org/about/}}</ref>  The program encourages the students to participate in service to the local community and provides technical assistance to the families of program participants ensuring that they apply for educational assistance programs ([[Pell Grant]]s, [[PHEAA]] grants, etc.) offered by the state and federal government.\n \nA report issued by the National Student Clearinghouse  concludes that participants in CORE are more likely than their fellow non-CORE classmates to complete their college education in four years.<ref>{{cite web|title=CORE Annual Report 2011|url=http://www.corescholars.org/core-scholarships-annual-report-2011/|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130414142702/http://www.corescholars.org/core-scholarships-annual-report-2011/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-04-14}}</ref>\n\n====Youth mentoring====\nFattah was the lead Democrat responsible for the funding of the [[United States Department of Justice]] and the [[United States Attorney General]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Fattah Statement at Subcommittee Markup of the FY13 Commerce, Justice, Science Appropriations Bill|url=http://democrats.appropriations.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=965&Itemid=17|access-date=2012-08-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120915080218/http://democrats.appropriations.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=965&Itemid=17|archive-date=2012-09-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=October 2016}} Since 2011, the Congressman was able to negotiate an increase of $30M to investment in DOJ programs that fund groups including the [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America]] and [[Big Brothers Big Sisters of America]].{{citation needed|date=September 2012}}\n\nIn 2012, Fattah negotiated a partnership between [[FIRST]] and Boys & Girls Clubs of America to provide robotics programs to 4 million youth by 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=FIRST \u00ae Announces Strategic Alliance with Boys & Girls Clubs of America|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/first-announces-strategic-alliance-boys-211200140.html|publisher=Yahoo Finance|access-date=2017-01-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509231948/http://finance.yahoo.com/news/first-announces-strategic-alliance-boys-211200140.html|archive-date=2012-05-09|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Neuroscience====\nFattah was the lead Democrat responsible for funding some of the largest science agencies in the federal system (NASA, NSF, Office of Science and Technology Policy (OSTP).<ref>{{cite web|title=Committee on Appropriations- Democrats|url=http://democrats.appropriations.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=84&Itemid=17|access-date=2012-09-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120915074956/http://democrats.appropriations.house.gov/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=84&Itemid=17|archive-date=2012-09-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{failed verification|date=October 2016}} In December 2011, Fattah through his role on the Appropriations Committee, directed the OSTP to establish an Interagency Working Group on Neuroscience (IWGN).<ref>{{cite web|title=Fattah Neuroscience Amendment Passes|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/fattah-neuroscience-amendment-passes-151901895.html}}</ref>  Housed within the White House and chartered on June 20, 2012, the IWGN convenes representatives across the Federal government to make recommendations about the future of neuroscience research.\n \nThe Fattah Neuroscience Initiative is a policy initiative designed to make major progress understanding the human brain by intensifying, in a collaborative fashion, federal research efforts across brain disease, disorder, injury, cognition and development.<ref>{{cite web|title=FATTAH NEUROSCIENCE INITIATIVE|url=http://fattah.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=295&sectiontree=4,295|archive-url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20120809110406/http://fattah.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid%3D295%26sectiontree%3D4%2C295|url-status=dead|archive-date=2012-08-09}}</ref> The initiative aims to coordinate Federal research across agencies and draw upon public-private partnerships and the world of academia. The initiative promotes research and discovery across brain cognition, development, disease and injury.\n\n====Manufacturing====\nFattah states that his priority is ensuring that small and medium businesses have the tools they need to prosper in an increasingly competitive global marketplace. He is the lead Democrat responsible for funding the Department of Commerce and the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative.{{citation needed|date=October 2016}} In his role on the Appropriations Committee, Fattah has advocated to $128 million in funding for the Manufacturing Extension Partnership, a program that assists small and mid-sized manufacturers create and retain jobs, increase profits, and save time and money.  He is also an advocate for the SelectUSA program, an initiative that encourages U.S. businesses operating off-shore to return to the U.S. and promote the U.S. marketplace.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fattah Speech before the Manufacturing Extension Partnership Summitt|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jkRD91hRx14}}</ref>\n\n====Cooperative development====\nFattah was considered a \u201ctrue champion\u201d of the co-op movement by the American Co-op Association.<ref>{{cite web|title=Congressman Fattah Introduces Legislation to Support and Incentivize Co-ops|url=http://www.generocity.org/congressman-fattah-introduces-legislation-to-support-and-incentivize-co-ops/|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222184520/http://www.generocity.org/congressman-fattah-introduces-legislation-to-support-and-incentivize-co-ops/|archivedate=2014-02-22}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, Fattah introduced the Creating Jobs through Cooperatives Act (HR 2437). This legislation will provide means to catalyze cooperative development, provide tools to entrepreneurs to bring cooperative to their communities, partner with financial institutions to provide grants a loans to developing businesses, offer technical training and professional development.<ref name=\"Creating Jobs through Cooperatives Act\">{{cite web|title=HR2437|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/bills/113/hr2437}}</ref> His bill calls for $25 million federal investment and technical assistance to cooperatives through a new National Cooperative Development Center. The bill has national support from co-op and EOB advocates and members.<ref>{{cite web|title=Legislation|url=http://www.campaign.coop/legislation|publisher=Campaign for Cooperation|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121228164918/http://campaign.coop/legislation|archivedate=2012-12-28}}</ref>  Co-ops have a broad base and connection to community in the Philadelphia area.<ref>{{cite web|title=Congressman Fattah shows co-ops in Philly\u2014and nationwide\u2014some holiday love|url=http://www.citypaper.net/blogs/nakedcity/Congressman-Fatah-shows-co-ops--love.html|publisher=Philly.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121012115126/http://www.citypaper.net/blogs/nakedcity/Congressman-Fatah-shows-co-ops--love.html|archivedate=2012-10-12}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013, Fattah was invited to attend as Keynote speaker at the Annual Cooperatives Conference, hosted by the NCBA. The conference brought together national leaders in cooperative development to share best practices to create powerful change for their organizations.<ref name=\"Annual Cooperatives Conference\">{{cite web|title=2012 ACC keynote speakers|url=http://www.ncba.coop/nov/322-2013-annual-cooperatives-conference-keynote-speakers|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223005434/http://www.ncba.coop/nov/322-2013-annual-cooperatives-conference-keynote-speakers|archivedate=2014-02-23}}</ref>\n\n===Sponsored legislation===\nAs a member of Pennsylvania\u2019s state House Fattah wrote and passed into law Pennsylvania\u2019s Homeowners Emergency Mortgage Assistance Program (HEMAP).<ref>{{cite web|title=Homeowners' Emergency Mortgage Assistance Program (HEMAP)|url=http://www.phfa.org/consumers/homeowners/hemap.aspx|publisher=Pennsylvania Housing Finance Agency|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816004716/http://www.phfa.org/consumers/homeowners/hemap.aspx|archivedate=2012-08-16}}</ref>  HEMAP is a loan program designed to protect Pennsylvanians who, through no fault of their own, are financially unable to make their mortgage payments and are in danger of losing their homes to foreclosure. Started in 1983 by Pennsylvania\u2019s Act 91 of 1983, it was only one of its kind until 2010 when Fattah added language to the Dodd Frank bill to provide similar assistance, to homeowners nationwide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fattah, HUD Dep. Secretary Sims Unveil Emergency Homeowners Loan Program|url=http://pennsylvania.realestaterama.com/2010/10/07/fattah-hud-dep-secretary-sims-unveil-emergency-homeowners-loan-program-ID0395.html|publisher=RealEstateRama}}</ref>  The Emergency Homeowners Loan Program provides up to 24 months of assistance, through bridge loans, for distressed homeowners and is a scaled-up version of the HEMAP program.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mortgage relief program aimed at foreclosures |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/inq_ed_board/Mortgage_relief_program_aimed_at_foreclosures.html |newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|publisher=[[Philadelphia Media Network]], LLC |date=October 18, 2013 |accessdate=2015-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Elmer|last=Smith |title=Fattah, Casey swoop in to help families facing foreclosure |url=http://articles.philly.com/2011-05-10/news/29528435_1_bridge-loans-hemap-borrowers |newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|publisher=[[Philadelphia Media Network]], LLC |date=May 10, 2011 |accessdate=2015-07-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Fattah served as a vice chair on the House Gun and Violence Taskforce, a taskforce created under the direction of House Democratic Leader Nancy Pelosi. The taskforce included both liberal and conservative Democrats, gun owners and Representatives from various cities. Fattah received an F rating from the [[National Rifle Association]] and an A+ rating from the Coalition on Gun Violence and the Brady Campaign to Prevent Gun Violence for his positions on gun control.\n\nSince 2006, Fattah has \u201cpioneered gun-buyback programs\u201d in Philadelphia with the Philadelphia Police.  The program offers Philadelphians the chance to exchange firearms for vouchers for groceries or other goods.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://votesmart.org/interest-group/1564/rating/5581#.VRw46uRVK1E |title=National Rifle Association Political Victory Fund Rating - The Voter's Self Defense System |publisher=Vote Smart |date= |accessdate=2016-04-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Fattah|first=Chaka |title=Fattah cites 'no-brainer' steps for gun control |url=http://articles.philly.com/2013-03-01/news/37354747_1_universal-background-checks-gun-violence-gun-control |newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|publisher=[[Philadelphia Media Network]], LLC |date=March 1, 2013 |accessdate=2015-07-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Fattah introduced a [[Bill (proposed law)|bill]] titled the \"Transform America Transaction Fee,\" (H.R. 3759) which proposed to have the [[U.S. Treasury]] conduct a one-year feasibility study of a 1 percent transaction fee imposed on transactions made at any financial institution. He touted the possibility that such a system would bring in so much money it would allow for greatly increased federal spending, saying the \"excess funds\" would \"provide universal health care, support an equitable public school finance system, and fund economic development in urban and rural areas,\" in addition to extinguishing the national debt and eliminating all other federal taxes.<ref>[http://www.factcheck.org/2010/09/1-transaction-tax/ 1% Transaction Tax]. ''FactCheck.org''. Retrieved on 2011-01-14.</ref> The bill died without attracting any co-sponsor. In 2005, Fattah introduced the bill again with H.R. 1601, and again in 2007 with H.R. 2130 which had a single cosponsor, Democratic Rep. [[Brian Baird]] of Washington. Both bills died without any action being taken. In 2009, Fattah introduced a fourth bill to require having a study conducted, H.R. 1703, which attracted no cosponsors. On February 23, 2010, Fattah reintroduced the bill as the \"Debt Free America Act,\" (H.R. 4646) which proposed to repeal the federal income tax and replace it with a 1 percent \"transaction tax\" on every financial transaction \u2014 whether paid by cash, credit card or any form of financial transfer, the only exception being transactions involving the purchase or sale of stock.<ref>Davis, Lanny. (July 6, 2010) [http://thehill.com/opinion/columnists/lanny-davis/107351-a-debt-free-america-yes-its-possible A debt-free America? Yes \u2014 it\u2019s possible]. ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]''. Retrieved on 2011-01-14.</ref> The latest bill places more focus on eliminating the federal debt. Fattah has also added a 1 percent tax credit designed to eliminate the impact of the measure on couples making less than $250,000 a year. As of September 5, 2010, none of the House committees have scheduled any action on the latest bill.\n\nIn 2005, Fattah opposed the [[War in Iraq]] and supported Congressman [[John Murtha]]'s call for troop withdrawal.<ref name=IRAQ>[http://www.pjvoice.com/v7/7300words.html An Interview with Congressman Chaka Fattah] ''The Philadelphia Jewish Voice''.</ref> He publicly supported the \u201cBring Our Troops Home and Iraq Sovereignty Act\u201d a bill that called for bringing the troops home within six months and transitioning the Iraqis to self-government.\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Appropriations|Committee on Appropriations]]'''\n**[[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Commerce, Justice, Science, and Related Agencies|Subcommittee on Commerce, Justice, Science, and Related Agencies]] (Ranking Member)\n**[[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on Energy and Water Development|Subcommittee on Energy and Water Development]]\n\n== 2007 mayoral election ==\n{{Main|2007 Philadelphia mayoral election}}\n\nIn November 2006, he declared his candidacy for [[List of mayors of Philadelphia|Mayor of Philadelphia]],<ref name=\"MAYOR\">[http://www.philly.com/mld/philly/16048207.htm It\u2019s official: Chaka Fattah is in the mayor\u2019s race] Philadelphia Inquirer</ref> where two-term incumbent Mayor [[John F. Street]] was barred from re-election by [[term limit]]s, amid pressure from Democratic voters to keep his Congressional seat in order to maintain a Philadelphia representative on the powerful [[U.S. House Committee on Appropriations|Appropriations Committee in the House]]. His candidacy announcement took place next to the recently completed [[Microsoft's School of the Future|Microsoft School of the Future]] in the city's Parkside neighborhood to emphasize his campaign platform of better educational opportunities for city youth.\n\nAfter emerging as a mayoral candidate, Fattah came under fire from the Philadelphia [[Fraternal Order of Police]] for his repeated calls to grant a new trial to [[Mumia Abu-Jamal]], who was convicted of murdering police officer [[Daniel Faulkner]] in 1981;<ref name=\"FOP\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thenextmayor.com/vault/20061201mumia.html |title=Fattah draws FOP wrath over Abu-Jamal issue |accessdate=2007-01-07 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927215510/http://www.thenextmayor.com/vault/20061201mumia.html |archivedate=September 27, 2007 }} The Philadelphia Daily News</ref> he also was criticized for possibly unethical campaign spending, based on new campaign finance rules adopted by the city of Philadelphia.  The Fattah campaign defended itself, claiming that it had followed less restrictive federal rules in spending the money,<ref name=\"CAMPAIGNFINANCE\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thenextmayor.com/vault/20070209fattah_exploratory.html |title=Fattah campaign may have used 'exploratory' $ |work=The Philadelphia Inquirer |date=February 9, 2007 |via=thenextmayor.com |access-date=April 20, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927215416/http://www.thenextmayor.com/vault/20070209fattah_exploratory.html |archive-date=September 27, 2007 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> but eventually returned a portion of the excess contributions to the [[exploratory committee]] following a settlement with the city's Board of Ethics.<ref name=\"CAMPAIGNFINANCE\" />  Fattah eventually came in fourth in the Democratic primary, close behind fellow Congressman [[Bob Brady]] but well behind former city councilman [[Michael Nutter]], who went on to win the fall [[2007 Philadelphia Mayoral Election|general election]] handily.\n\n==2016 indictment and conviction==\n\nIn August 2014, Fattah's longtime aide and close confidant Gregory Naylor pled guilty to federal charges in a complex money laundering scheme used to hide an illegal million-dollar loan that a candidate, unnamed in that indictment, received for his failed mayoral campaign in 2007. The loan was paid back using federal grant money intended for nonprofit organizations affiliated with Fattah.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roebuck|first1=Jeremy|title=Former aide's guilty plea raises questions for U.S. Rep. Chaka Fattah|url=http://articles.philly.com/2014-08-29/news/53329550_1_younger-fattah-guilty-plea-chaka-jr|website=Philly.com|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref> A subsequent Philadelphia Daily News investigation revealed that nonprofits receiving federal funding and connected to Fattah paid out over $5.8 million to Fattah allies and alleged that many of these payments were ethically dubious.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bender|first1=William|title=Fattah nonprofits paid millions to ex-staffers|url=http://articles.philly.com/2014-10-09/news/54790460_1_fattah-jr-nonprofits-staffers|website=philly.com|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn July 29, 2015, Fattah and four of his associates, Bonnie Bowser, Karen Nicholas, Herbert Verderman and Robert Brand were indicted for their alleged roles in a [[racketeering]] [[Conspiracy (criminal)|conspiracy]] involving several schemes that were intended to further the political and financial interests of the defendants and others by, among other tactics, misappropriating hundreds of thousands of dollars of federal, charitable and campaign funds. The FBI further alleged that Fattah accepted an $18,000 bribe from a man seeking an ambassadorship.<ref name=\"fbi2015\">{{cite press release |url=https://www.fbi.gov/philadelphia/press-releases/2015/congressman-chaka-fattah-and-associates-charged-with-participating-in-racketeering-conspiracy |title=Congressman Chaka Fattah and Associates Charged with Participating in Racketeering Conspiracy |publisher=[[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] |date=July 29, 2015 |accessdate=2015-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Roebuck|first1=Jeremy|last2=Fazlollah|first2=Mark|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/news/20150803_Fattah_case_was_built_over_years.html|title=Fattah Case Was Built Over Years|newspaper=The Philadelphia Inquirer|date=August 3, 2015|accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe trial was originally scheduled for May 2, 2016, but in April a judge had the date pushed back to May 16 to give the defendants time to review the excess of more than 100,000 documents accrued by the prosecution.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://6abc.com/politics/fattah-corruption-trial-testimony-pushed-back-to-may-16/1279698/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425174055/http://6abc.com/politics/fattah-corruption-trial-testimony-pushed-back-to-may-16/1279698/|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-04-25|title=Fattah corruption trial testimony pushed back to May 16|website=6abc Philadelphia|access-date=2016-04-29}}</ref>\n\nOn June 21, 2016, Fattah was convicted of all charges, including racketeering conspiracy, bribery, bank fraud, mail fraud, money laundering, making false statements to a financial institution, and falsification of records.<ref name=\"inquirer-2016-06-21\">{{cite news | title = Fattah convicted of federal corruption charges | journal = The Philadelphia Inquirer | date = June 21, 2016 | last1 = Roebuck | first1 = Jeremy | url = http://www.philly.com/philly/news/politics/20160622_Fattah_convicted_of_federal_corruption_charges.html | access-date=2016-06-21 }}</ref> He announced his immediate resignation from Congress two days later, on June 23.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fox29.com/news/164915086-story|title=Congressman Chaka Fattah resigning immediately after conviction|last=FOX|work=WTXF|access-date=2018-11-06|language=en-US}}</ref> Just days later, the U.S. Supreme Court issued its decision in ''[[McDonnell v. United States]]'' which altered the legal definition of bribery to exclude \"pay for access.\" On the basis of this ruling, Fattah appealed his conviction in October 2016, placing his sentencing on hold.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.phillytrib.com/news/fattah-sentencing-on-hold/article_199b65e8-ab8c-57e9-837a-b34ee4735799.html|title=Fattah sentencing on hold|last=Jones|first=Ayana|date=|work=|newspaper=The Philadelphia Tribune|access-date=2016-11-10|via=}}</ref>\n\nOn December 12, 2016, Fattah was sentenced to 10 years in prison.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/12/chaka-fattah-sentencing-10-years-232507|title=Fattah sentenced to 10 years in prison|last=Bresnahan|first=John|date=|work=|website=POLITICO|access-date=2016-12-12|via=}}</ref> He reported for prison at [[Federal Correctional Institution, McKean]] near [[Lewis Run, Pennsylvania]] on January 25, 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mcall.com/news/nationworld/pennsylvania/mc-pa-convicted-congressman-fattah-20170125-story.html|title=Chaka Fattah reports to federal prison to begin 10-year sentence|last=|first=|date=January 25, 2017|work=|access-date=2017-03-24|via=|newspaper=The Morning Call}}</ref>\n\nOn August 9, 2018, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit in Philadelphia overturned Fattah's bribery convictions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www2.ca3.uscourts.gov/opinarch/164397p.pdf|title=PRECEDENTIAL UNITED STATES COURT OF APPEALS FOR THE THIRD CIRCUIT |last=|first=|date=August 9, 2018|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref>\n\nThe Court of Appeals remanded for a new trial as to certain bribery and money laundering counts, concluding that the jury had not been properly instructed regarding \u201cofficial acts\u201d in a bribery context.\u00a0 (The government thereafter announced its intention not to retry those counts.)\u00a0 With regard to the government\u2019s cross-appeal, the Court of Appeals reinstated certain counts that had been dismissed by the District Court post-trial. The case was then remanded for resentencing. \u00a0\n\nFor these additional counts, Fattah was again sentenced to 10 years of incarceration on July 12, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov/usao-edpa/pr/former-us-congressman-chaka-fattah-sr-resentenced-10-years-incarceration-corruption|title=Former U.S. Congressman Chaka Fattah, Sr., Resentenced to 10 Years of Incarceration for Corruption Convictions |last=U.S. Attorney\u2019s Office|date=July 12, 2019|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\nIn the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2016|2016 election]], Fattah was ousted in the Democratic primary\u2013the real contest in his heavily Democratic, black-majority district\u2013to state representative [[Dwight E. Evans|Dwight Evans]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2016/04/26/congressman-chaka-fattah-loses-longstanding-seat-to-rep-dwight-evans/|title=Congressman Chaka Fattah Loses Longstanding Seat To Rep. Dwight Evans|date=26 April 2016|access-date=2016-04-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.phillyvoice.com/chaka-fattah-concedes-loss-pursuit-12th-term-congress/|title=Chaka Fattah concedes loss in pursuit of 12th term in Congress|website=PhillyVoice|date=27 April 2016|access-date=2016-04-29}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2014|2014 election]], Fattah received 181,141 votes, or 87.7% of the vote, to 25,397, or 12.3%, to his Republican opponent, Armond James, a school teacher with no prior political experience.<ref>Pa. Dept of State at www.electionreturns.state.pa.us</ref> This was a significant decrease from the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2012|2012 election]], when Fattah received 302,746 votes, more votes than any other member of the House of Representatives for that election.<ref>{{cite news|last=Snyder|first=SyS|title=11/16 Ups & Downs|url=http://www.politicspa.com/1116-ups-downs/44331/|date=2012-11-16}}</ref>\nFattah was challenged by Republican nominee Robert Allen Mansfield, Jr. and Independent candidate and publisher of the Germantown Newspapers, Jim Foster.<ref>{{cite web|title=Foster for Reform|url=http://www.foster4reform.org|access-date=2018-11-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161008042900/http://foster4reform.org/|archive-date=2016-10-08|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n*'''2010 Race for U.S. House'''<ref>\"[http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/ElectionsInformation.aspx?FunctionID=13&ElectionID=39&OfficeID=11 2010 General Election: Official Returns] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101106003151/http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/ElectionsInformation.aspx?FunctionID=13&ElectionID=39&OfficeID=11 |date=2010-11-06 }}\". ''Pennsylvania Department of State''. November 2, 2010.</ref>\nFattah was challenged by Republican nominee Rick Hellberg, the CEO of a small financial firm.\n**Chaka Fattah ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]) (inc.), 89%\n**Rick Hellberg ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]), 11%\n[[United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2010#District 2|See also: United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2010#District 2]]\n\n*'''2008 Race for U.S. House'''<ref>\"[http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/ElectionsInformation.aspx?FunctionID=13&ElectionID=28&OfficeID=11 2008 General Election: Official Returns] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208193742/http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/ElectionsInformation.aspx?FunctionID=13&ElectionID=28&OfficeID=11 |date=2008-12-08 }}\". ''Pennsylvania Department of State''. November 4, 2008.</ref>\n**Chaka Fattah (D) (inc.), 89%\n**Adam Lang (R), 11%\n*'''2007 Democratic Primary  for Mayor of Philadelphia'''\n**[[Michael Nutter]]     106,805        36.64%\n**[[Tom Knox]] \t         71,731 \t24.61%\n**[[Bob Brady]]          44,474 \t15.26%\n**Chaka Fattah       44,301 \t15.20%\n**[[Dwight E. Evans|Dwight Evans]]           22,782 \t7.82%\n**Totals \t        291,492 \t100%\n*'''2006 Race for U.S. House'''\n**Chaka Fattah (D) (inc.), 89%\n**Michael Gessner (R), 9%\n*'''2004 Race for U.S. House'''\n**Chaka Fattah (D) (inc.), 88%\n**Stewart Bolno (R), 12%\n*'''2002 Race for U.S. House'''\n**Chaka Fattah (D) (inc.), 88%\n**Tom Dougherty (R), 12%\n*'''2000 Race for U.S. House'''\n**Chaka Fattah (D) (inc.), 98%\n**Ken Krawchuk ([[Libertarian Party (United States)|L]]), 2%\n*'''1998 Race for U.S. House'''\n**Chaka Fattah (D) (inc.), 86%\n**Anne Marie Mulligan (R), 14%\n*'''1996 Race for U.S. House'''\n**Chaka Fattah (D) (inc.), 88%\n**Larry Murphy (R), 12%\n*'''1994 Race for U.S. House'''\n**Chaka Fattah (D), 86%\n**Lawrence Watson (R), 14%\n\n==Personal life==\nFattah is married to his third wife, [[Renee Chenault-Fattah]], a former Philadelphia television news broadcaster on [[WCAU|WCAU-TV]] (NBC 10). They have one daughter, Chandler Fattah. He is stepfather to her daughter Cameron Chenault. With other women, he is the father of another daughter, Frances (\"Fran\"), and one son, Chaka Fattah Jr., known as \"Chip\",<ref>{{cite news | first=Maryclaire|last=Dale | title=US Rep's son says he's 'collateral damage' in bid to get dad | agency=[[Associated Press]] | date=March 22, 2015 | url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/5fc8b3c15d224c719faa42ce325f0f81/us-reps-son-says-hes-collateral-damage-bid-get-dad | quote=\"Chip Fattah \u2014 reed-thin and always smiling \u2014 can talk a blue streak. But he paused, atypically, when asked how long he had lived with his father, a 10-term Philadelphia Democrat, before his parents divorced. His sister, Fran, is a lawyer running for city judge. Fattah Sr., 58, also has two young daughters with his third wife, local TV anchor Renee Chenault-Fattah.\" | accessdate=2015-03-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Dianna|last=Marder |url=http://articles.philly.com/2001-04-08/news/25330143_1_chaka-fattah-dark-chocolate-cake-wedding-cake |title=Party politics: Fattah, Chenault exchange vows With help from their children, the congressman and the news anchor held a big church wedding. |newspaper=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] |publisher=[[Philadelphia Media Network]], LLC |date=April 8, 2001 |accessdate=2015-07-29}}</ref> who was convicted of felony bank and tax fraud in February 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/local/Chaka-Fattah-Jr-Fraud-Sentencing-Federal-Court-367332741.html|title=Congressman's Son Heading to Prison|website=NBC 10 Philadelphia|access-date=2016-04-29}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, he was named to the [[PoliticsPA]] list of Best Dressed Legislators, noting his \"excellence in haberdashery.\"<ref name=bestdressedlegislators>{{cite web| title =Sy Snyder's Best Dressed Legislators| work =[[PoliticsPA]]| publisher =The Publius Group| year =2002| url =http://www.politicspa.com/FEATURES/best_dressed.htm| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20020803093934/http://www.politicspa.com/FEATURES/best_dressed.htm| archivedate =2002-08-03| url-status =dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of African-American United States Representatives]]\n*[[List of American federal politicians convicted of crimes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n*{{Curlie|Regional/North_America/United_States/Pennsylvania/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Chaka_Fattah_%5BD-2%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=f000043 | votesmart=21850 | fec=H2PA02055 | congress=chaka-fattah/371 }}<!-- Links formerly displayed via the {{CongLinks}} template:\n* [http://ballotpedia.org/Chaka_Fattah Biography] at [[Ballotpedia]]\n* [http://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/400130 Congressional profile] at [[GovTrack]]\n* [http://www.opencongress.org/people/show/400130 Congressional profile] at [[Participatory Politics Foundation|OpenCongress]]\n* [http://www.rollcall.com/members/409.html Congressional profile] at ''[[Roll Call]]''\n* [http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00001746 Financial information (federal office)] at [[Center for Responsive Politics|OpenSecrets.org]]\n* [http://apps.washingtonpost.com/politics/capitol-assets/member/chaka-fattah Financial investments (personal)] at ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n* [http://www.legistorm.com/member/228/Rep_Chaka_Fattah.html Staff salaries, trips and personal finance] at LegiStorm.com\n* [http://www.ontheissues.org/PA/Chaka_Fattah.htm Issue positions and quotes] at [[On the Issues]]\n* [http://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n2002-27615 Works by or about Chaka Fattah] in libraries ([[WorldCat]] catalog)\n* [http://www.c-spanvideo.org/person/36763 Appearances] on [[C-SPAN]] programs\n* [http://www.imdb.com/name/nm2180629 Appearances] at the [[Internet Movie Database]]\n* [http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/gIQAvQNqAP_topic.html Collected news and commentary] at ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n* -->\n*{{C-SPAN|Chaka Fattah}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n| state=Pennsylvania\n| district=2\n| before=[[Lucien E. Blackwell|Lucien Blackwell]]\n| after=[[Dwight E. Evans]]\n| years=1995&ndash;2016}}\n{{s-par|us-pa-sen}}\n{{succession box | before= [[Freeman Hankins]] | title= Member of the [[Pennsylvania State Senate|Pennsylvania Senate]] for the [[Pennsylvania Senate, District 7|7th District]]